	   <a name=97573087322324></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f97573087322324><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=97573087322324>My particular reason for using the fire pet</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=97573087322324#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=606><span id=Sage>Yegolev</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>192 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Dec 1st 11:21 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Yeah, yeah, I know. Hear me out, though. Lately I have been using the fire pet with good success lately and it is because I took a tip from our "friends" the necromancers. Note that I almost exclusively solo.<br><br>One day I realized that there was no reason whatsoever for me to be at full health. I really only need one point of health to survive the fight, so why not put my other points to good use? I happen to have a dagger of dropping and I will often step in and poke the mob with it, however the reason I step in is not to do damage, it's to sponge damage. I am at the Oasis stage of life, and crocs hit pretty hard, especially the yellow ones, but I want to tell you that you need to take one for the team, so to speak. I usually let the mob beat on me until I'm at one to one and a half bubbles left before I back off, and this gives my fire pet plenty of time to pour on the damage and regen some. I usually issue a '/pet notaunt' if I'm having trouble holding the mobs attention, but usually they come after me anyway.&nbsp;&nbsp;The important part is to step in closer than your pet and you'll get wacked every time. Remember that's damage your little summoned DoT isn't taking, and if it dies you're toast anyway.<br><br>You should also remember that you can summon bandages which is essential to getting back to half health.  In this amount of time your pet can heal a good bit. Using this strategy you will also see a large improvement in mana conservation, so throw a few heals on your pet and jump back into it. Smart mages will realize you can do all this 'maintenance' during the fight. If I have no need to bandage myself, I at least med a few seconds once I am sure I'm going to win.  If things get ugly, back up and gate... maybe Sparky won't like it, but he'll be dead soon anyway, eh?<br><br>I'm not saying this is the best route, and I have the deaths to prove it (I have been doing this wearing just a Senior Apprentice Robe and partial small cloth armor), but I think that this role is very well-suited to the fire pet.<br>&nbsp;<br>www.yegolev.com<br>Ibaler the Valewalker<br>Gaheris</td></tr>
